T1  - Bubbles, Fads and Stock Price Volatility Tests: A Partial Evaluation
AU  - WEST, KENNETH D.
Y1  - 1988/07/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1988.tb04596.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 639
EP  - 656
VL  - 43
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1988.tb04596.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This is a summary and interpretation of some of the literature on stock price volatility that was stimulated by Leroy and Porter [28] and Shiller [40]. It appears that neither small-sample bias, rational bubbles nor some standard models for expected returns adequately explain stock price volatility. This suggests a role for some nonstandard models for expected returns. One possibility is a ?fads? model in which noise trading by naive investors is important. At present, however, there is little direct evidence that such fads play a significant role in stock price determination.
ER  - 

